<br>
The process is easy. Go to the web site and find your state. Look for an item that has not been pledged or sent. Send an email to the webmaster with your pledge. Next follow the link to the item you (or your club, it can be a group effort) pledged to buy and purchase it with a ship to address for your Senator (important!). Make sure to fill out the comment or gift field so the Senator knows why they received the item! We have an example note on the web site.<br>
<br>
When you receive your email receipt from the vendor forward it to the web master, Jimmy Yawn at jyawn@sfcc.net . Jimmy will then update your pledge to show &quot;fufilled.&quot;<br>
<br>
Items being pledged include:<br>
The October Sky Video<br>
Handbook of Model Rocketry by G. Harry Stine<br>
Model Rocket Design and Construction by Tim Van Milligan (Apogee Components)<br>
A Quark Star model rocket kit from Doug Pratt (Pratt Hobbies)<br>
<br>
Tim Van Milligan has kindly offered to ship 100 copies of Model Rocket Design and Construction books to Doug Pratt and sell them for $18.00 a copy instead of the usual $24 price. By ordering through the Pratt Hobbies web site you can purchase both the Quark Star kit and Tim's book at the same time! Doug, additionally has offered to include your FAX or email in the package to your Senator. If you want to send Doug a FAX for insertion into your package please call 1-866-522-1251 to send your document. It will be forwarded to Doug. We do recommend that you send a FAX or email to Tim or Doug explaining to your Senator why they should support Senator Enzi's bill.<br>
<br>
Please keep your total package below $50, otherwise the Senator may be unable to accept the package due to government rules. There are plenty of Care Packages to go around! Also, remind your Senator to contact Candice Cotton (224 - 3424) on Senator Enzi's staff to further discuss this issue if they have questions.<br>
<br>
We need to educate our representatives about the hobby. Do it now before the ATF does it.<br>
<br>
If all of these items are pledged, paid for, and shipped in a very brief time - like immediately, if not sooner, then it is likely that a media-worthy event could occur. With help from rocketeers in the Washington, DC area, we can possibly assemble rocketeers and community groups (clubs, scouts, church, schools) to hand-deliver the goodies and give great sound bites and visual images for the media. Go to this web site to make a pledge: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.jamesyawn.com/senate/index.html">www.jamesyawn.com/senate/index.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iz55>iz55</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 41<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/20/03 1:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  preserving the freedom to launch - stand up and be counted!</span><hr size=1> The initiative to educate all senators about hobby rocketry still needs your support!  While rocketeers in several states have shown 100% support, many states have had no action taken at all.  There are rocketry clubs in virtually every state in the U.S., including Alaska and Hawaii!  The movement to preserve the freedom to enjoy all areas of non-commercial rocketry requires the broadest support.<br>
<br>
Low-power or &quot;model&quot; rocketry enthusiasts may mistakenly believe that their sport is not effected by the 62.5g exemption; that an illusion propagated by the ATFE.  While LEUP (Low Explosive User Permits) are not presently required for motors smaller than 62.5g, there are shipping restrictions which apply to Black Powder (of which Estes and Quest motors are made) that make even these motors unavailable.  Many shipments to the Team America Rocketry Challenge high school participants have been suspended due to refusal of shippers to carry rocket motors of any size.<br>
<br>
Users of mid-, high- amateur and experimental rocketry materials are additionally affected by the LEUP requirement.  The &quot;Limited&quot; users permit offered by the ATF is virtually useless, as it is unlikely that the motors can be purchased within your home state.  Many rocketeers also launch in neighboring states, and regional and national launches are completely inaccessible to holders of the &quot;Limited&quot; users permits!<br>
<br>
As a result if these conditions, many surveyed businesses that supply rocketry materials have said that they see going out of business inevitable.  Many of these businesess are small or family-operated, and their livelihood it risk.  These are the companies that have strived to provide the broad range of materials, the innovative devices and the competitive prices that have allowed rocketry in all forms to thrive over the past few years.<br>
<br>
Do not believe that &quot;someone else&quot; will be saving your freedoms for you,  An effective democracy depends upon the feedback of it's citizens.  Every affected individual must stand up and be counted if they wish to preserve rocketry for themselves, their children, school children across the U.S. and for the next generation.<br>
<br>
Please visit the following sites to pledge your support to educate the Senators in your state.<br>
<br>
information about the initiative:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.jamesyawn.com/senate/index.html">www.jamesyawn.com/senate/index.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
status of contributions by state:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.jamesyawn.com/senate/pledge.html">www.jamesyawn.com/senate/pledge.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
